estoring historical contours to a leading aspect of cultural interchange in this century. At the same time, the book successfully embeds Weimar cinema in its contemporary international setting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aMotion picturesxHistoryxGermany. 0aMotion pictureszGermanyxHistory. 0aMotion pictures, AmericanxInfluencexGermany. 0aMotion pictures, AmericanzGermanyxInfluence. 0aMotion pictures, GermanxInfluencexUnited States. 0aMotion pictures, GermanzUnited StatesxInfluence. 0aNational characteristics, American, in motion pictures. 0aNational characteristics, German, in motion picturesxGermanyxUnited States. 0aNational characteristics, German, in motion pictureszGermanyzUnited States. 0aNational characteristics, German, in motion pictures. 4aEurope. 4aEuropean history. 4aGermany. 4aHollywood. 4aarchitecture. 4acinema. 4aculture. 4afilm. 4ahistory of architecture. 4ahistory of art. 4ahistory of the Americas. 4ahistory. 4aphilosophy. 4apolitical philosophy. 4asocial philosophy. 4asociety. 4athe arts. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091416240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520914162423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520914162/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles